document.title: Mathematics Standards of Learning for Virginia Public Schools

9BD735011E6D475AB4122FEC67B03AD8.description: Verify the commutative and associative properties for matrix addition and multiplication.

E896C6F5C7A44911863C39BE4602A4DB.description: Verify two matrices are inverses using matrix multiplication.

98601BCD57F141D6AF5F775D7D40EF43.description: Determine the inverse of a two-by-two or three-by-three matrix using paper and pencil.

F82E654046364BBB8C9B165381BC3A8C.description: Solve a system of equations using matrices.

5B3044DFD5FD43348C4520E68751FC9F.description: Express a system of linear equations as a matrix equation.

3427B5F881B940ACA75D7827D3302BDC.description: Represent problems with a system of no more than three linear equations.

20CF43333C7848C5AD397B78C00AC27E.description:
The student will use matrices to organize data and will add and subtract matrices,
multiply matrices, multiply matrices by a scalar, and use matrices to solve systems of
equations.

BA7C9A9AB11041B3B7DA8D242F0147BB.description:
Determine and verify the intersection of the graphs of two polar equations, using graphing
technology.

5BDADCEBB48647B0BB228A90F2F9C8AC.description: Convert equations between polar and rectangular forms.

63CF3B04261C4D22A68F763CD9343E29.description: Convert between complex numbers written in rectangular form and polar form.

9BF99895F04841A89D843DE74AE3CB58.description: Convert between polar and rectangular forms of coordinates.

985D12375D864D51800F1DBD5A763526.description:
Determine the effects of changes in the parameters of polar equations on the graph, using
graphing technology.

B4350D0E57904124AA0CB5D68DFCDCEC.description:
Classify polar equations (rose, cardioid, limaçon, lemniscate, spiral, and circle), given the
graph or the equation.

BEDAE4349A6D4C1CBB026ED442A57E38.description:
The student will investigate and identify the characteristics of the graphs of polar
equations.

B28943B59EB447989A251993FDCCD353.description: Apply vectors to problems in context.

8B810AB0C9294045AB5D16D932FCB5C9.description: Find a unit vector in the same direction of a given vector.

7A2F9D30A9C64CEB9CF16BF6D5EA9440.description: Determine the norm (magnitude) of a vector.

CDAFB5F63BEC4A819656E55DC382109A.description: Determine the components of a vector.

10BB35240B4D4E138479B4FCEF176C4C.description: Verify properties of the dot product.

FC7200E287FC471CB5670A54F3E96B25.description: Express complex numbers in vector notation.

B83BA671DB764946A58C5EB09B87F067.description: Determine if two vectors are orthogonal.

9737810A77854880ADA6F3E67ABC8A9E.description:
Find the dot (inner) product of two vectors and use it to determine the angle between two
vectors.

4B568D4C1B2147D49E8B8019F201609B.description:
Perform the operations of addition, subtraction, and scalar multiplication, graphically and
algebraically on vectors.

FE8629F2155643F5BD6B4BCDCDB14D1B.description: The student will perform operations with vectors in the coordinate plane.

3E4E957F85264183B7541D89037E4AEE.description: Use parametric equations to model contextual problems, including motion over time.

81F452787C07499A961067A2F1A04C6B.description: Graph and analyze parametric equations and use the graph to determine solutions.

74493AA616E749A49EA97C69818FC330.description: The student will use parametric equations to model and solve problems in context.

75C3373FA305430EAAB90E8D22B73185.description:
Identify characteristics of conic sections including center, vertices, axes, symmetry, foci,
directrix, eccentricity, and asymptotes.

8FEE4B3272BE405C860A8DFEE8BA0251.description:
Graph conic sections from equations written in general or standard form using
transformations.

BCF4C38C9A67448894EA042EC268F7FD.description: Convert between standard and general forms of conic equations by completing the square.

3A725AC88B7E411B90CF17B9E1A4DEB2.description:
Given a translation or rotation matrix, determine an equation for the transformed function or
conic section.

2E3A22AE183C4DD88C1B0E3B7259B9B4.description:
The student will identify and analyze the properties of conic sections and sketch a
graph given an equation.

F2A61596FEFA47928979DF0227C1AD70.description: Describe convergent series in relation to the concept of a limit.

722CFB7E365143C390E3EA667D1556F9.description: Distinguish between a convergent and divergent series.

2175AE79DC9A4CAAAC796216CDA975EE.description: Model and solve problems in context, using sequences and series.

1B752C1BCBD9413FAF52F3102AAB08D4.description: Determine the sum, Sn, if it exists, of an arithmetic or geometric series.

F16A7913E64E47FAAF139DBB9E4A19DD.description: Determine the nth term, an, for an arithmetic or geometric sequence.

398EE89EE2C546E78EB270C1FF889B42.description: Derive the formulas associated with arithmetic and geometric sequences and series.

23B1FA4CAC0E4DA6A41D6BCD61ABF14A.description:
Use and interpret the notation: ∑, n, n
th, and an.

93397C470E8747BEBDC02D693EED66B9.description:
The student will analyze sequences and finite series, and model and solve problems
in context using sequences and series.

80A428DEBAE1491183A03FD5027FE495.description:
Sketch the graph of exponential and logarithmic functions and identify asymptotes, end
behavior, intercepts, domain, and range.

6AEA91F4ED98450C84B6E670523B5FD0.description:
Represent contextual problems, using exponential and logarithmic functions, to include
common and natural logarithms.

BB0A22CF27DA45B292D3F7374BC5069E.description:
Use laws of exponents and properties of logarithms to solve equations and simplify
expressions.

72CCFE3D6EEE447389C94CAFFB9EF6D0.description: Convert between equations written in logarithmic and exponential form.

8CCFEA2DF5ED4FDAA755F5CCFC3F5FBA.description: Define e and estimate its value.

E20A7F4628814B338DD8B6CB79B086B5.description:
Generalize characteristics of exponential and logarithmic functions from an equation or a
graph.

B49D835F569F4012A92150253E72A546.description:
The student will analyze the characteristics of exponential and logarithmic functions,
and sketch the graphs of the functions.

E6DA9D01432A486580C2430C0D9BF10E.description:
Use mathematical reasoning to generalize and communicate the criteria for an inverse
function to exist.

5B210DD6D4B041D1A6431363A7FAC306.description:
Compare the domain and range of the inverse of a function with the original function, both
algebraically and graphically.

31AF81065ACD42CC8FC3FF63D611558B.description: Develop the inverse of a function algebraically and graphically.

96270207EA194D279E0CF032DA28BD34.description: Determine the domain and range of composite functions algebraically and graphically.

4C77C587A1564B8BB88B3EE39250B034.description: Construct the composition of functions algebraically and graphically.

21B8CE6F29E04772AD23C6143E659E06.description:
The student will analyze compositions of functions to determine and verify inverses
of functions.

0A72B3893C4047BAB73B900D72E06BB5.description: Classify types of discontinuity based on which condition of continuity is violated.

88AC6AE43CEF43879B3FC4F7F5655A27.description: Prove continuity at a point, using the definition.

218B2823F9FA40C8AFA6BC9B8B84D391.description:
Use mathematical notation to communicate and describe the continuity of functions including
polynomial, rational, piecewise, absolute value, radical, and step function, using graphical and
algebraic methods.

DFE473E1D58046E58794C85B1A19F0D2.description: The student will analyze and describe the continuity of functions.

44F13B610113453CB933C141A9E2BB3E.description:
As the variable approaches positive or negative infinity, analyze the limit of a function to
describe the end behavior.

32B06E781FF443DB8CD7FA0A31977FD4.description: determine the limit of a function from a given graph.

D52B47EBA14E45EA8D46432631C03499.description: estimate the limit of a function using a table; and

67993A826288468B9398610E41DACB34.description: determine the limit of a function using algebraic manipulation;

5E57874429EC427D84307183FC54ED1E.description: determine the limit of a function numerically by direct substitution;

67AAEFC4A360466A8CEEDBFB7F7ACDEB.description: As the variable approaches a finite number,

6F149A84E6AD47EAAF3F9F4CAE3A2545.description: Use proper limit notation, including when describing the end behavior of a function.

0AF56706B7ED4E03B1C85770EB9FE56A.description: Determine the limit of a function numerically and verify with graphing technology.

4F9598D661E7407C83E466A8C8278C6D.description: Determine the limit of a function algebraically and verify with graphing technology.

C07D21AE2C754CDE8ADFC76793B99D3F.description: Verify estimates about the limit of a function using graphing technology.

399EB6FDBD6B48B29435591793BC0A78.description: The student will determine the limit of a function if it exists.

3DB606132DB84821AABF387A85B7A0FE.description:
Sketch the graph of a polynomial, rational, piecewise-defined, absolute value, radical, and
step function.

78ADE582A0034F3DA3B47E767216ECCC.description: relative and/or absolute maximum and minimum points.

7790DDF1D69648229A9D95C75D667059.description: intervals for which the function is increasing, decreasing or constant;

DC751AD6E28D4BEC8E5382C7FDC86817.description:
Given multiple representations of a polynomial, rational, piecewise-defined, absolute value,
radical, and step function, analyze:

33B33777725D4B0B911DBF572A65E7E1.description:
Use mathematical reasoning to identify polynomial, rational, piecewise-defined, absolute
value, radical, and step functions, given an equation or graph.

578EE668FC14491FA8BDDD663D43BDD5.description:
The student will identify and analyze the properties of polynomial, rational,
piecewise-defined, absolute value, radical, and step functions and sketch the graphs
of the functions.
